===Past Awards & Rankings===
UC San Diego Medical Center was named among the best in the nation by [[US News and World Report]] in 2007 in six specialty areas. UCSD Medical Center ranked 8th in [[respiratory disease|respiratory disorders]], 18th in [[rheumatology]], 30th in [[kidney disease]], 30th in [[gynecology]], 39th in [[cancer]], and 50th in [[otolaryngology|ear, nose, and throat]].<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=America's Best Hospitals 2007: University of California, San Diego Medical Center | date= | publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]] | url =http://health.usnews.com/usnews/health/best-hospitals/directory/hospital.php?id=6932820 | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2007-10-16 | language = |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071012092021/http://health.usnews.com/usnews/health/best-hospitals/directory/hospital.php?id=6932820 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-12}}</ref> In 2009, the UC San Diego Medical Center once again was named among the best in the nation by US News and World Report in six specialty areas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards |first=Kim |url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/newsrel/health/07-09Excellence.asp |title=Continuing Excellence: UC San Diego Medical Center Among Nation’s Best |publisher=Ucsdnews.ucsd.edu |date=2009-07-16 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref> UC San Diego Medical Center ranked 14th in respiratory diseases, 20th in [[psychiatry]], 21st in rheumatology, 39th in [[urology]], 43rd in kidney diseases, and 47th in cancer.

==Hillcrest Medical Center==
The UC San Diego Medical Center, Hillcrest ({{coord|32.75442|-117.166009|display=inline}}), is the primary hospital for the University of California, San Diego School of Medicine.

The region's only academic medical center offers both primary care and specialized services, including a full range of surgery, diagnosis and management of genetic disease, neurology, orthopedics, oncology, and the Sleep Medicine Center.

The recently renovated 386-bed hospital at UC San Diego Medical Center, Hillcrest, is also the primary site for such regional services as the Comprehensive Organ Transplant Program,
Bone Marrow Transplantation, San Diego Regional Burn Center, Infant Special Care Center (NICU), UCSD's Birth Center, San Diego County's only academic Level One Trauma Center, and the National Institutes of Health-designated Clinical Research Center.

==Thornton Hospital==
The John M. and Sally B. Thornton Hospital and Perlman Ambulatory Care Center ({{coord|32.879225|-117.223717|display=inline}}) opened in the summer of 1993. John Alksne, a neurosurgeon and the [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the School of Medicine, performed the first surgery at this hospital. It was a delicate brain operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.ucsd.edu/news/history.htm |title=History and Milestones at UCSD Medical Center |publisher=Health.ucsd.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref> It is located on the UCSD campus in La Jolla, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.ucsd.edu/locations/thornton.htm |title=UCSD's Thornton Hospital's Address, Directions, Map & Phone Number |publisher=Health.ucsd.edu |date=2007-09-25 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref> It is a 119-bed general medical-surgical facility that offers a full range of services, including [[surgery]], [[cardiology]], [[endocrinology]], [[neurology]], [[orthopedics]], [[oncology]], [[reproductive medicine]], [[pulmonary medicine]] and [[physical therapy]]. Thornton Hospital has a hotel-like atmosphere and patients staying in the intermediate care wing of the hospital can order room service meals at any time of the day.<ref>{{cite web|author=POSTED: 1:29 pm PDT June 5, 2006 |url=http://www.10news.com/health/9323434/detail.html |title=Hospital Serves Up Room Service To Patients - Staying Healthy News Story - KGTV San Diego |publisher=10news.com |date=2006-06-05 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref>

==Rebecca and John Moores UCSD Cancer Center==
Established in 1979, the Rebecca and John Moores UCSD Cancer Center is one of just 39 National Cancer Institute-designated Comprehensive Cancer Centers in the United States. Such centers are prominent among the leading institutions in the nation dedicated to scientific innovation and clinical excellence. UCSD is the only Comprehensive Cancer Center in San Diego and Imperial counties to have earned this honor.

In 2007, [[US News and World Report]] ranked the UCSD Medical Center 39th in the nation for cancer treatment.
<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Best Hospitals 2007 Specialty Search: Cancer | date= | publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]] | url =http://health.usnews.com/usnews/health/best-hospitals/search.php?spec=ihqcanc | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2007-10-16 | language = }}</ref>

==Shiley Eye Center==
The UCSD Shiley Eye Center provide comprehensive eye care services, from basic eye exams to advanced diagnostic tests and sophisticated surgery.  Eye care services offered at UCSD Shiley Eye Center include cataract surgery, cornea transplants, glaucoma diagnosis and treatment, low vision services, neuro-ophthalmology, optometry and contact lens service, pediatric ophthalmology, plastic surgery, refractive surgery, retina care, and trauma repair.

The Abraham Ratner Children's Eye is immediately adjacent to Shiley and is the only eye facility in the San Diego region dedicated to meeting the special vision needs of children.

==Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center==
As part of the La Jolla Campus construction. UC San Diego Health Systems is planning to open the new {{convert|128000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility, which will provide ambulatory, clinical, and inpatient heart and stroke care in one central location.<ref name="edwards1">{{cite news | first=Kim | last=Edwards | coauthors= | title=UC San Diego Health System Opens New North County Cardiology Clinic | date=2010-11-23 | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego Health System]] | url =http://health.ucsd.edu/news/2010/11-23-north-coastal-cardio-clinic.htm | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2010-11-23 | language = }}</ref>

==North Coastal Cardiology Clinic==
As part of providing health care to all areas of the county with the opening of the Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center to residents in Northern Part of San Diego. UCSD Health Systems opened in November 2010, the North Coastal Cardiology Clinic was opened in Encinitas, CA <ref name="edwards1"/>

==Plans==
On May 18, 2007, the UC Regents approved a plan to build an additional 125- to 150-bed inpatient tower in La Jolla.<ref>{{cite news | first=Leslie | last=Franz | coauthors= | title=Regents Approve Plan for New UCSD Inpatient Bed Tower | date=2007-05-18 | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego Medical Center]] | url =http://health.ucsd.edu/news/2007/5_17_Regents.htm | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2007-10-16 | language = }}</ref>

On November 19, 2010, the UC Regents approved a plan to build a new building for Clinical and Translational Institute (CTSI). This building is planned to have 311,000 gross square feet at a cost of $269 million.<ref>{{cite news | first=Alex | last=Philippidis | coauthors= | title=UPDATE: UC Board of Regents OKs $269M Clinical and Translational Building for UCSD | date=2010-11-19 | publisher=[[GenomeWeb Daily News]] | url =http://www.genomeweb.com/uc-board-regents-oks-269m-clinical-and-translational-building-ucsd | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2010-11-29 | language = }}</ref>

